# The Children of Fear — Campaign Overview (Keeper background)

*A Keeper-facing summary of the campaign's premise, structure, and central
lore, synthesized from the Campaign Overview and the player-knowledge/handout
appendices. Structure and stats live in the `.campaign`/`.arc`/`.actor` files;
this captures the big picture a Keeper needs. Consult your copy of the campaign
for the full text, boxed read-aloud passages, and the physical handouts.*

## Premise

An epic, player-led *Call of Cthulhu* campaign set in 1923–24, tracing the old
Silk Road pilgrim route of the 7th-century Chinese Buddhist monk and explorer
Hiuen-Tsiang (Xuanzang) — from China across Central Asia into northern India and
hidden Tibet. The investigators are drawn from a mundane archaeological errand
into a metaphysical crisis: the balance between the mythic twin kingdoms of
**Shambhala** and **Agartha** is failing, the Gates of Agartha are opening, and a
prophesied figure — the **King of Fear** — stands to escape into the world.
Whether the investigators help avert this, hasten it, or are undone by it is the
spine of the campaign.

## The central lore (Shambhala, Agartha, and the King of Fear)

Esoteric tradition entwines two hidden kingdoms. **Shambhala** is generally cast
as a luminous Pure Land — a paradise of preserved knowledge and enlightenment,
watched over by its Lords and the line of the Kalika (Kalki) kings. **Agartha**
is its darker counterpart/underside — variously its capital, its shadow, or its
prison. The campaign hangs on the reading (which the Keeper selects) of how these
relate and how the **King of Fear** — an ancient adversary of the Kalika and the
Lords of Shambhala — is bound within Agartha and might break free as evil rises.
Framing this is the Hindu cosmology of **cyclical time**: Brahma's out-breath
creates a universe and his in-breath ends it; each day is a thousand *Mahayugas*,
each divided into the four *yugas* (Golden, Silver, Bronze, and the present dark
*Kali Yuga*) — the age of decline in which the campaign is set, when such a
reincarnation and such a threat come due.

## Scalable Mythos

The Keeper tunes how cosmic the threat is, from the **Outer Gods themselves** at
one extreme down to a **low-key, occult-focused intrigue** at the other. Several
key NPCs carry Luck and Pulp traits so the campaign can be run as **Classic** or
**Pulp Cthulhu**. The Overview supplies the Keeper's decision points on the
threat's true nature.

## Structure

- **Campaign Overview** — the setting, the Shambhala/Agartha background, keeper
  considerations, the dramatis personae, investigator motivations, and a glossary.
- **Chapter 1 — The City of Decaying Splendor (Peking):** recruitment. The
  investigators are hired to aid the explorer **Langdon Warner** at the Caves of
  the Thousand Buddhas at Tun-huang, and the hidden **Tokabhaya** begin watching
  them.
- **Chapter 2 — To the Gates of the Sun (Chang'an/Tun-huang):** the journey west
  and an extraordinary plea from a strange ***lama*** — to help save reality, for
  the Gates of Agartha are opening as chaos rises.
- **Chapters 3–5 — attempted in any player-chosen order:** travelling with the
  *lama* across India and Tibet to gather the items needed to "close" the Gates —
  Ch3 (Gandhara / the Northwest Frontier; the alms bowls; Peshawar), Ch4 (Old
  Bones; Rajgir/Sitavana), Ch5 (Feast and Famine; the Land of Snows; Derge). A
  key thread: locating the *real* ritual able to keep the King of Fear from
  escaping, which requires the fabled **Hell Chambers at Patna** built by Emperor
  **Ashoka**.
- **Chapters 6–8 — Liberation, Spirits of the Earth, The Heart of the World:** the
  convergence and climax, where the campaign's outcome is decided.

## Investigator motivations (hooks)

The Overview offers ready reasons to be on the expedition, which the Keeper can
assign or let players choose — e.g. **proving oneself** to doubters; **a way out**
of debt/crime/a ruined deal; **King and Country** (duty to employer, loved ones,
faith, or nation); and **Money Talks** (simply being well paid). Adventuring
investigators can also be New York Explorers Club members on a Central Asiatic
expedition, and academics can be lecture-circuit guests via the China Lecture
Association (the Chapter 1 hook).

## Running it: travel and tone

Distances are vast, so the campaign leans on the **Travel by Map** device
(red-lining the route à la *Pulp Cthulhu* / adventure serials), dropping provided
*en-route* encounters to build mounting strangeness rather than resolving every
mile. **Dark Materials:** the campaign handles human remains, ritual sacrifice,
and related themes — the Overview urges Keepers to check in with their players and
use safety tools. **Naming:** 1920s-common place/person names are used (with
BCE/CE dating except on in-character handouts).

## Recurring threat cast

- **The King of Fear** — the prophesied adversary bound in Agartha; the campaign's
  looming antagonist.
- **The Tokabhaya** — its agents/lieutenants, surveilling and manipulating the
  investigators from Chapter 1 onward (psychic intrusion, imposed visions).
- **The *lama*** — the strange holy man of Chapter 2 whose quest the middle
  chapters serve.
- **Langdon Warner** — the archaeologist whose plea launches the investigators
  (Chapter 1 hook; stats with Chapter 2's cast).
